clinical_study.brief_title: Enhancing STDP After Spinal Cord Injury
clinical_study.official_title: Maximizing Spike - Timing Dependent Plasticity After Spinal Cord Injury

lead_sponsor.agency: VA Office of Research and Development

clinical_study.source: VA Office of Research and Development

brief_summary.textblock: The overall goal is to develop new clinical approaches to restore upper-limb function after incomplete cervical spinal cord injury (SCI). Corticospinal tract (CST) axons are involved in controlling upper-limb function. Paired pulse induced spike-timing dependent plasticity (STDP) enhances synaptic strength between residual CST axons and spinal motoneurons (SMNs) resulting in temporary improvements in upper-limb function in humans with incomplete cervical SCI. Motor training will be combined with paired-pulse STDP stimulation to further enhance plasticity and behavioral recovery.

study_design_info.masking_description: participants will not know if they receive real or sham stimulation

primary_outcome.measure: Amplitude of Motor Evoked Potential (MEP) From TMS
primary_outcome.time_frame: Measured before and after the STDP during the 2-hour session for Arm 1 and measured at baseline and post all training sessions during the 2-hour session for Arm 2 and 3.
primary_outcome.description: We measure amplitude of a motor evoked potential evoked by transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) before and after the 30 minute STDP intervention. For STDP + Training and Sham STDP + Training we measured the MEPs at baseline and post all training sessions.

secondary_outcome.time_frame: Measured before and after the STDP during the 2-hour session for Arm 1 and measured at baseline and post all training sessions during the 2-hour session for Arm 2 and 3.
secondary_outcome.description: We measure maximum voluntary contraction (MVC) of muscles recorded by electromyography (EMG) before and after the 30 minute STDP intervention. For STDP + Training and Sham STDP + Training we measured MVC at baseline and post all training sessions.

secondary_outcome.measure: The Graded Redefined Assessment of Strength Sensibility and Prehension (GRASSP)
secondary_outcome.time_frame: Measured at baseline and post all training sessions in the 2-hour session
secondary_outcome.description: The GRASSP assessment is a standardized test of functional abilities of the hand. We measure time required to complete the GRASSP test from baseline to post 10 training sessions. The time is recorded in seconds.

arm_group.description: Paired stimulation will be given to the brain and to a peripheral nerve so that the messages are received at the spinal cord at predetermined time.
Paired stimulation will be given to the brain and to a peripheral nerve so that the messages are received at the spinal cord at predetermined time. Motor training will follow paired stimulation.

Sham or fake paired stimulation will be given to the brain and to a peripheral nerve so that the messages are received at the spinal cord at predetermined times. Motor training will follow stimulation.

intervention.description: Paired stimulation will be given to the brain and to a peripheral nerve so that the messages are received at the spinal cord at predetermined time.
The participant will be asked to perform exercises using their hands and arms.
Sham or fake paired stimulation will be given to the brain and to a peripheral nerve so that the messages are received at the spinal cord at predetermined times.

criteria.textblock:
Inclusion Criteria:
Participants who are unimpaired healthy controls:
- Male and females between ages 18-85 years
- Right handed
- Able to complete precision grips with both hands
- Able to complete full wrist flexion-extension bilaterally
- Able to walk unassisted
- Able to complete full ankle flexion-extension bilaterally
Participants who have had a spinal cord injury:
- Male and females between ages 18-85 years
- SCI ( 6 months of injury)
- Spinal Cord injury at or above L5
- The ability to produce a visible precision grip force with one hand
- Able to perform some small wrist flexion and extension
- The ability to perform a small visible contraction with dorsiflexion and hip flexor muscles
- No subjects will be excluded based on their race, religion, ethnicity, gender or HIV status.
- ASIA A,B,C, or D
Exclusion Criteria:
Exclusion criteria for enrollment For SCI and Healthy Control Subjects (4-8 exclusion for non-invasive brain stimulation only):
- Uncontrolled medical problems including pulmonary, cardiovascular or orthopedic disease
- Any debilitating disease prior to the SCI that caused exercise intolerance
- Premorbid, ongoing major depression or psychosis, altered cognitive status
- History of head injury or stroke
- Metal plate in skull
- History of seizures
- Receiving drugs acting primarily on the central nervous system, which lower the seizure threshold (see appendix 2)
- Pregnant females
- Ongoing cord compression or a syrinx in the spinal cord or who suffer from a spinal cord disease such as spinal stenosis, spina bifida, MS, or herniated disk
- Individuals with scalp shrapnel, cochlear implants, or aneurysm clips.

group.title: STDP
group.description: Paired stimulation (STDP) will be given to the brain and to a peripheral nerve so that the messages are received at the spinal cord at predetermined time. STDP: Paired stimulation will be given to the brain and to a peripheral nerve so that the messages are received at the spinal cord at predetermined time. Participants will complete study visits each lasting ~2 hours. Changes in TMS measurements in the form of motor evoked potentials (MEPs) will be measured before and after the 30 minute STDP intervention. The maximum voluntary contraction (MVC) will be measured using surface EMG before and after the 30 minute STDP intervention.

group.title: STDP + Training
group.description: Paired stimulation (STDP) will be given to the brain and to a peripheral nerve so that the messages are received at the spinal cord at predetermined time. Motor training will follow paired stimulation. STDP: Paired stimulation will be given to the brain and to a peripheral nerve so that the messages are received at the spinal cord at predetermined time. Training: The participant will be asked to perform exercises using their hands and arms. Participants will complete 10 STDP + Training study visits each lasting ~2 hours. Baseline and post measurements will be collected. The following measurements were collected: Changes in TMS measurements in the form of motor evoked potentials (MEPs). Changes in the maximum voluntary contraction (MVC) will be measured using surface EMG. Functional measurement, GRASSP, will measure changes in the time it takes to complete hand tasks.

reported_events.time_frame: The adverse event data is collected from baseline to completion of study visits, an average of 35 weeks. The longer experiment arm involves 100 sessions = 20 weeks at 5 sessions per week, and the final follow-up is at 3 months after the final session = 12-15 weeks later. This gives a total of 32-35 weeks.
reported_events.desc: Arm 1 includes all participants who were monitored for adverse events even if they did not complete the study visit.
